labored in the fields -- t20: The urge to speak in verse burst forth -- t21: Wealth elevates the children of the vulgar herd -- t22: No use praying for the return of the days -- t23: If a dumb ox comes asking for your daughter’s hand -- t24: Prosperity sparkles like a heady wine -- t25: Yesterday at the well Khalīfah accosted me -- t26: Listen carefully, my boy, to this wise old man -- t27: I swear by God and by all that is holy -- t28: Time is pregnant, events are its midwife -- t29: Ibn Nḥēṭ, listen carefully to these polished verses -- t30: These are the words of an old graybeard -- t31: Smart fellows, heed this piece of advice -- t32: This is the faith that is as clear -- t33: If you head for al-Qaṣab you’ll find me to its south -- t34: Things are simple and easy at the start -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tFurther Reading -- tIndex -- tAbout the NYU Abu Dhabi Institute -- tAbout the Translator -- tThe Library of Arabic Literature0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSatirical verse on society and its hypocrisiesA master of satire known for his ribald humor, self-deprecation, and invective verse (hijāʾ), the poet Ḥmēdān al-Shwēʿir was an acerbic critic of his society and its morals. Living in the Najd region of the Arabian Peninsula, Ḥmēdān wrote in an idiom widely referred to as “Nabaṭī,” here a mix of Najdī vernacular and archaic vocabulary and images dating to the origins of Arabic poetry. In Arabian Satire, Ḥmēdān is mostly concerned with worldly matters and addresses these in different guises: as the patriarch at the helm of the family boat and its unruly crew; as a picaresque anti-hero who revels in taking potshots at the established order, its hypocrisy, and its failings; as a peasant who labors over his palm trees, often to no avail and with no guarantee of success; and as a poet recording in verse how he thinks things ought to be.The poems in Arabian Satire reveal a plucky, headstrong, yet intensely socially committed figure—representative of the traditional Najdī ethos—who infuses his verse with proverbs, maxims, and words of wisdom expressed plainly and conversationally. Ḥmēdān is widely "ed by historians of the Gulf region and in anthologies of popular sayings. This is the first full translation of this remarkable poet.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh1 aKurpershoek, Marcel.1 aTylus, Jane.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831107227030 cprintz978147988516940uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479846764.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479846764423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479846764/original  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070474-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-072270-3  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-DKUb2020